# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-football
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The **12th man** or **12th player** is a collective term for fans of sports teams in many eleven-a-side games, in particular association football.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] As most football leagues allow a maximum of eleven players per team on the playing field at a time, referring to a team's fans as the 12th man implies that they have a potentially helpful and significant role in the game.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The presence of fans can have a notable impact on teams' performance, an element in the home advantage.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Namely, the home team fans would vocally support and urge on their team to win the game.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Thus, these fans will often create loud sounds or chant in the hope of encouraging their team, or of distracting, demoralizing, or confusing the opposing team while they have possession of the ball, or to persuade a referee to make a favorable decision for the team.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Noises are made by shouting, singing, whistling, stomping, clapping, and various other techniques.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In Canadian football, 12 players from each team are usually on the field at one time and the term **13th man** is often used to refer to fans.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Similarly, in Australian rules football, 18 players are on the field, and the fans are often referred to as the **19th man**.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] However, in basketball, where five players are on the court, the term *Sixth man* generally refers to an energetic substitute player.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Similarly, in rugby sevens, with seven players from each team on the field, "Eighth man" is not used to refer to fans as the term refers to the eighth forward in rugby union.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The term *Twelfth Man* has a specifically different meaning in cricket, referring instead to the nominated first substitute player who fields when a member of the fielding side is injured during play.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The first recorded use of the term "twelfth man" was a magazine published by the University of Minnesota in September 1900, that referred to "the mysterious influence of the twelfth man on the team, the rooter".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Later, in the November 1912 edition of *The Iowa Alumnus*, an alumni publication of the University of Iowa (then known as State University of Iowa), E.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] McGowan described the 1903 game between Iowa and the University of Illinois.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The 1922 Dixie Classic served as the setting for an event later referred to as "The story of the 12th Man".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] This football game featured the top-ranked Centre College and The Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas (later known as Texas A&M).
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Bible realized that one more injury would leave him without another backfield player to send into the game.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] King Gill, a sophomore basketball player, down from the stands to stand ready as a substitute.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Gill was ready in uniform on the sidelines if his team needed him.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Individuals have occasionally been labeled by local media as the "Twelfth Man" of their team.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Adamson, Principal of Oak Cliff (Dallas) High School was called the "Twelfth Man" of the school's American football team by a local reporter due to the rousing pre-game speeches he would give to the players.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Likewise, sometimes, fans of both teams in an annual contest have been described as the 12th man.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Bears currently use the phrase "4th Phase" (with the first three phases being offense, defense, and special teams), and the Seahawks currently use the phrase "The 12s".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Many high schools in the United States incorporate 12th man language into their booster, supporter, or rooter clubs.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Examples of such "12th Man Clubs" include the Dana Hills Dolphins, Washington Panthers, Richwood Knights, Diamond Bar Brahmas, Fairfield Falcons, and Brentwood Bruins.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Campbellsville University Tigers of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics also have a 12th Man Club.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] On December 12, 1992, (12/12/1992) the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League honored their 12th Man as the seventh inductee into the Buffalo Bills Wall of Fame, located inside Highmark Stadium.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Their fans were inducted because of their loyal support during the team's early '90s Super Bowl runs, which coincided with quarterback Jim Kelly and his wearing of #12.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In 2008, the Bills renamed their "12th Man Walk of Fame" as "Tim Russert Plaza", in honor of the recently deceased Buffalo native and lifelong fan.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The team continues to refer to its fans as the "12th Man", with their independent, international fan clubs known as "Bills Backers Chapters".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Bills have a licensing agreement with Texas A&M over the use of the "12th Man" term.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] From 2007 to 2016, fans of the Indianapolis Colts of the NFL were known as the 12th Man.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Colts created a Ring of Honor on September 23, 1996, after playing 13 seasons in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In 2007, the Colts inducted their 12th Man as the sixth entrant into the team's Ring of Honor, then located on the interior facade of the RCA Dome.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Ring of Honor currently encircles Lucas Oil Stadium, the team's home venue.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The organization also designates a "12th Man Fan of the Game".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M announced the filing of a lawsuit against the Colts based on the team's usage of the term.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] On February 17, 2016, the lawsuit was settled with the Colts agreeing to remove the phrase from their Ring of Honor and to immediately cease all other uses of the trademarked phrase.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Seattle Seahawks retired the number 12 jersey on December 15, 1984, in honor of their fans.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In 2003, the Seahawks installed a giant flagpole in the south end zone of what is now Lumen Field, and began a tradition of raising a giant flag with the number 12 on it in honor of the fans, one of whom is Sam Adkins, the former Seahawks quarterback who did wear the number 12.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Usually, a local celebrity or a season ticket holder raises the flag during pregame ceremonies.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In recent years, 12th Man flags have been seen all over Seattle whenever the Seahawks make the playoffs, including atop the Space Needle.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In 2014, Boeing painted a Boeing 747-8 freighter aircraft with a special Seahawks livery, with the number 12 on the tail, and they later flew it over eastern Washington in a flight path spelling the number 12.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] When the Seahawks took the field for Super Bowl XLVIII, they were led by LB Heath Farwell carrying the team's 12th Man flag per team tradition.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In May 2016, mountaineer David Liaño González displayed a 12th Man flag at the summit of Mount Everest.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] As per an agreement struck between the Seahawks and Texas A&M in 2016, the Seahawks have virtually ceased from referring to their fans as the "12th Man", and instead are using the term "12s" or the 12 Fan.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The first known instance of Texas A&M referring to its fanbase as the "12th Man" is contained on page 17 of the November 25, 1921, edition of *The Battalion*, the Texas A&M campus newspaper.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] King Gill left the stands in 1922; the entire student body stood throughout the game to symbolize their "readiness, desire, and enthusiasm" to take the field if needed.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Football coach Jackie Sherrill created the "12th Man Kick-Off Team" in the 1980s, composed of non-athletic scholarship students who tried out for the team.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Coach Sherrill has written a book entitled "No Experience Required" which details this team and the tradition.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] These students were placed on the roster for the sole purpose of kickoffs.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The squad was nicknamed "the suicide squad".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] These students often had little regard for their safety and were determined to make a tackle at any cost.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The 12th Man Kick-Off Team was extremely successful and eventually held opponents to one of the lowest yards-per-return average in the league during kickoffs.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Slocum changed the team to allow only one representative of the 12th Man on the kickoff team who wears uniform number 12.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The player is chosen based on the level of determination and hard work shown in practices.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Under Dennis Franchione, the 12th Man Kick-Off Team, composed of walk-ons, was brought back, though used only rarely when the team was up by quite a few points.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] On June 30, 2014, Texas A&M bought the domain name 12thman.com, which then became its official athletics website.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In 1986, the Washington Redskins (now known as the Washington Commanders) released a video entitled "Thanks to the 12th Man".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The term "12th man" is commonly used in football to refer to the fans and occasionally the manager.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] A notable club famous for the twelfth man reference comes from Aston Villa, referring to the Holte End stand at Villa Park.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Large European teams such as Bayern Munich, Malmö FF, Hammarby IF, Helsingborgs IF, Werder Bremen, Aberdeen, Rangers, Lazio, PSV, Feyenoord, Ferencvárosi TC, FC Red Star, Fenerbahçe S.K., and Sporting CP have officially retired the number 12 to the fans.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Stockport County fans are registered as official members of their squad with the number 12.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Portsmouth F.C. has also retired its number 12 shirt, and lists the club's supporters, "Pompey Fans", as player number 12 on the squad list printed in home match programmes, while Plymouth Argyle have theirs registered to the *Green Army* (the nickname for their fans).
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] On Hammarby IF's, Helsingborgs IF, Malmö FF, Feyenoord and Werder Bremen's home games, the stadium speaker announces number 12 as "the fans" during team lineup announcements.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Dynamo Dresden in Germany also keeps number 12 for their fans, as well as the official team anthem being "We are the 12th man".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Aberdeen F.C. supporters commonly display a large banner in the shape of a football shirt with the text "Red Army 12" in place of a player's name and number.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The fans of the Northern Ireland national football team and Derry City are referred to as the 12th man as well.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In the League of Ireland, Shamrock Rovers F.C. retired the number 12 jersey in recognition of the fans who took over the club in 2005.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Cork City F.C., Clube Atlético Mineiro and Clube de Regatas do Flamengo also retired the number 12 for the fans.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The most vociferous fans of Boca Juniors in Argentina are known as the "Jugador Numero 12" (Spanish for "Player Number 12") or simply "La Doce" ("The 12").
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Lecce, an Italian team currently playing in Serie B, retired the number 12 to the fans, which was handed to them by the former captain Cristian Ledesma.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] They symbolically represent a 12th Man in the field.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In the beginning of 2009–2010 season, Happy Valley AA introduced the club's mascot, a panda, on squad list as the fan club captain wearing the number 12 jersey.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] As of the end of the 2011–2012 season, Rangers F.C announced that the number 12 jersey would be retired in honour of the fans support throughout a period of financial difficulty.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In American football, the sideline is sometimes also referred to as the "12th man" or "12th defender": since a player is considered down when he steps out of bounds, the sideline effectively acts as an extra defender.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] This usage is less common than the one referring to the fans.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In most sports the term can also be construed to mean the referee, implying that the match official favours one team and is not impartial.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The effects of the "12th man" vary widely, but can be put in two categories.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The first is simply psychological, the effect of showing the home team that they are appreciated, and showing the away team that they are somewhat unwelcome.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The second directly relates to the deafening effects of a loud crowd.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In Association football, the crowd can be very passionate and often sing throughout the whole match.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Some occasions where the crowd noise is extra loud can be before kickoff; during the buildup to and scoring of a goal; when encouraging the team to come back from defeat; to discourage an opposition penalty taker; or to harass a referee giving a free kick to the opposition team.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In American football, fans are most incited by physical play, especially good plays made by the defense.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Additionally, the home team can derive energy from the loud noise of their fans; former American football players have described the feeling of their adrenaline pumping after hearing the fans yell, which is "like you have a reserve energy tank".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The noise of the crowd can have a significant impact on the players on the field.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In American football, an extremely loud crowd can prevent the offensive linemen from hearing the snap count.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] This can have the effect of making the player slower to react when the ball is snapped, and his eventual response may be weaker than normal because each play is begun "with some indecision and doubt".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The noise can also prevent players from hearing audibles and can make it difficult for the team's offense to coordinate plays in the huddle.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The effect of the noise can often be measured in mistakes, such as false start penalties.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Coaches can take steps to minimize the effect of the crowd noise on their teams.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Some American football teams bring large speakers to their practice fields and broadcast loud noises such as jet engines to prepare their teams for the anticipated noise level.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Crowd noise tends to diminish after a long lull in play, such as a pause for instant replay.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Former NFL player Brian Baldinger speculates that some coaches draw out reviews as part of a coaching strategy to quiet the crowd for their next play.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] A researcher from Harvard University discovered in a study that some association football referees appeared to be impacted by crowd noise.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] His studies revealed that a home team acquired an additional 0.1 goal advantage for every 10,000 fans in the stadium.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Delia Smith, Norwich City's joint major shareholder, received some attention when she took to the pitch during a half time interval, with a microphone in hand and Sky TV cameras in tow, to tell fans the side "need their twelfth man".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Norwich City lost the game in the final seconds, but Smith's passion worked to increase the affection the fans held for her.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The current naturally loudest football stadium is Nef Stadium in Istanbul home of Galatasaray S.K.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] As a prepared attempt, the current world record for crowd noise at an athletic event was set on September 29, 2014, when the Kansas City Chiefs hosted the New England Patriots.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Noise during that event reached a high of 142.2 decibels during a timeout.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Texas A&M University applied on December 26, 1989, for trademark U.S.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The United States Patent and Trademark Office issued the "trademark registration" September 4, 1990, to Texas A&M.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Four additional Trademark claims related to the "12th Man" term were also filed and granted at later dates by Texas A&M University (See U.S.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] 74560726, 76671314, 85977835 and 85851199), the first three of which have achieved Incontestable Status as a result of its section 15 affidavit with the Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] According to former Texas A&M Athletic Director Bill Byrne, he contacted the Chicago Bears and Buffalo Bills about halting their "12th Man" themes.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Byrne stated that, "they responded quickly with our requests to stop using our Twelfth Man trademark".
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Texas A&M sent requests to stop using the phrase to the Seattle Seahawks in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The Seahawks did not respond to the requests.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In January 2006, Texas A&M filed a trademark infringement lawsuit against the Seattle Seahawks and in May 2006, the dispute was settled out of court.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] Neither side admitted any fault or liability.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In the agreement, the Seahawks licensed the phrase in exchange for $100,000, along with public acknowledgement as to Texas A&M's ownership rights of the phrase, and an additional annual fee.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The compensation amounted to $5,000 per year.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The agreement, which expired in 2016, limited the Seahawks' usage to seven western states and forbid them from selling any "12th Man" merchandise.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In August 2015, the Seahawks shifted towards calling their fans the "12s", and replaced their "Home of the 12th Man" stadium sign with a new "Home of the 12s" sign.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M filed suit against the Indianapolis Colts after repeated cease and desist requests were ignored by the NFL team.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] In August 2016, the Seahawks agreed to a new five-year trademark licensing agreement with Texas A&M.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] As part of the agreement, the Seahawks agreed to pay Texas A&M $140,000 for limited rights to use the trademarked term.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] This agreement, like the previous agreement, prohibits the Seahawks from using the "12th Man" term on any merchandise.
[src:american-football/12th-man-football] The new agreement, however, also prohibits Seattle from using the term on social media, nor are they allowed to use the term on any signage within their stadium, including their Ring of Honor.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:american-football/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The first American football game was played between teams from Rutgers College, now Rutgers University, and the College of New Jersey, now Princeton University, on November 6, 1869.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The rules governing play were based on the London-based Football Association's 1863 rules that disallowed carrying or throwing the ball making it the first intercollegiate soccer game in the United States.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Additionally, because gridiron football developed from the rules of association football and rugby football, many also consider it to be the first gridiron game and the first collegiate American football game.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The events leading up to the first college football game were described by John Warne Herbert Jr., in 1933.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Herbert was one of the players on the Rutgers team in the inaugural college football match and the youngest player in the game.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Rutgers and Princeton had a rivalry going for many years prior to their collegiate football match.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] For many years, Rutgers and Princeton engaged in a friendly war over a Revolutionary War cannon, known as the Rutgers–Princeton Cannon War.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Rutgers and Princeton students had gone back and forth between the colleges many times, which are just 20 miles apart.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] When Princeton last stole the cannon from Rutgers, then encased it on their campus in several feet of concrete, they left Rutgers without immediate recourse.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Princeton then demolished Rutgers in an intercollegiate baseball game, winning 40 to 2, in 1866.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Rutgers was looking for revenge and challenged Princeton to the football match.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Rutgers, through its elected captain, William J.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Leggett, then sent a formal invitation to play a series of three games, the first being on the Rutgers campus.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Princeton, which had been playing various forms of football internally since 1840, organized a team and chose William Stryker Gummere as its captain.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] On November 6, 1869, the Princeton students arrived in New Brunswick at 10 a.m. and the students all entered the Rutgers field at 3 p.m. that afternoon.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The two team captains established the rules of the game between each other and play began.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Part of the 1869–70 college soccer season and the first season of college football, the game took place on November 6, 1869, at a field on College Avenue (now the site of the College Avenue Gymnasium) in New Brunswick, New Jersey.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Because the game was played at Rutgers, it was also played under Rutgers' rules.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] They were based on the English Football Association's 1863 rules, in which two teams of 25 players attempted to score by kicking the ball into the opposing team's goal.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] A 1932 painting of the match by Rutgers graduate William Boyd illustrates the soccer-style ball and goalposts.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The teams played 10 "games" against each other.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] When a team scored a goal, it counted as the end of that game, and the team with the most goals after 10 games was the winner.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] It is clear that its format did not resemble the game of college football as known today.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The first such game in the United States in which the ball is advanced by physically picking it up and running, where play is stopped by knocking down the ball carrier, and each team fields eleven members was played on June 4, 1875, between Tufts and Harvard colleges. and then Yale on November 13.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] That game caused Yale to drop association football in favor of rugby.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Princeton was represented by the Tigers and Rutgers by the Queensmen.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Leggett, later a distinguished clergyman of the Dutch Reformed Church, was the Rutgers captain; William Gummere, who later became chief justice of the Supreme Court of New Jersey, captained the New Jersey squad.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The game was played in front of approximately 100 spectators.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The players from Rutgers wore scarlet-colored turbans and handkerchiefs to distinguish themselves from the Princeton players.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The scarlet of the Rutgers Scarlet Knights came from this episode.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] No throwing or running with the ball; if either it is a foul and the ball then must be thrown perpendicularly in the air by the side causing the foul.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] No holding the ball or free kicks allowed.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] A ball passing beyond the limit on the side of the goal shall be kicked on from the boundary by the side who has that goal.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] A ball passing the limit on the side of the field shall be kicked on horizontally to the boundary by the side which kicked it out.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The winner of the first toss has the choice of position; the winner of the second toss has the first kick-off.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] There shall be four judges and two referees.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] As the first of the 10 games began, two players from each of the teams positioned themselves near the opponent's goal.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] This was presumably because the participants were hoping to easily score when the ball reached their territory on the field of play.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] On each team, there were eleven so-called "fielders" who were assigned to defend their own territorial area.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] There were 12 participants on each team that they named "bulldogs" who were the ones playing in the other team's territory.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Rutgers was the first to score a goal, as Stephen G.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Gano and George Riley Dixon successfully kicked the ball across the Princeton goal.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] At some point early in the contest, the "flying wedge" play was first used as the team with the ball formed a wall-like formation of players, allowing them to charge at the defenders.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] This flying wedge tactic was successful early on for Rutgers because of their size disadvantage over Princeton.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] However, Princeton countered the tactic when Jacob Edwin Michael, better known as "Big Mike", broke up the Rutgers' Flying wedge during the fourth game.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Princeton took advantage and tied the score at 2–2.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] A Rutgers player named Madison Monroe Ball, a wounded veteran of the American Civil War, used his quickness and kicking the ball with the heel of his foot to again take the lead in the contest.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Whenever the ball entered Rutgers territory, Ball would get in front of it and use a heel-kick to prevent Princeton from scoring.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Ball was able to successfully use that technique to set up Dixon to score another goal which gave Rutgers a 4–2 lead.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Rutgers then allowed Princeton to score a goal as one of their players, whose identity is not known, had kicked a ball toward their own goal.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] It was blocked by a Rutgers player, but Princeton soon was able to take advantage to cut the lead down to 4–3.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The Tigers scored on their next possession when they used a flying wedge play of their own led by Big Mike to march down the field to score to tie the game again at 4.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Leggett had a strategy for his team at this point.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] He suggested that the Rutgers team keep the ball low on the ground to counter the much taller players on Princeton.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] This strategy appeared to work as Rutgers easily scored the final two goals of the contest to win the first intercollegiate football game played 6 games to 4.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Princeton had more size, which would normally be an advantage on a field with 50 total players, but the Tigers had trouble kicking the ball as a team which is something Rutgers did very well.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] In a 1933 account, a Rutgers player from the game named John W.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Herbert said that he thought Rutgers was the smaller team, but that they had more speed than Princeton .
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] According to a retrospective story, the winning Rutgers students immediately ran Princeton's players out of town, forcing them to hastily return home "in their carriages." This suggests that the game also birthed the first passionate college football rivalry.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] Fifty years after the historic first game, members of the 1869 Rutgers football team were honored at Homecoming ceremonies in 1918.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] The last surviving player of Princeton, Robert Preston Lane (b.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] 1851) died in November 1938, while the last surviving Rutgers player, George H.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] In 1968, Arnold Friberg was commissioned by Chevrolet to create a painting commemorating the game.
[src:american-football/1869-new-jersey-vs-rutgers-football-game] His work *The First Game* was one of four works that he created to celebrate 100 years of college football.
[src:american-football/1876-college-football-season] The **1876 college football season** had no clear-cut champion, with the *Official NCAA Division I Football Records Book* listing Yale as having been selected national champions.
[src:american-football/1876-college-football-season] On November 11, organized intercollegiate football was first played in the state of Pennsylvania as Princeton defeated Penn 6–0 in Philadelphia.
[src:american-football/1876-college-football-season] This season was notable in the history of American football as it saw Walter Camp, widely considered to be the "Father" of the sport, participate as a freshman on the Yale team.
[src:american-football/1880-college-football-season] The **1880 college football season** had no clear-cut champion, with the *Official NCAA Division I Football Records Book* listing Princeton and Yale as having been selected national champions.
[src:american-football/1880-college-football-season] On April 9, college football was first played in the state of Kentucky when Kentucky University defeated Centre 13⁠3/4⁠–0 at Stoll Field.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The 1925 National Football League (NFL) Championship which was awarded to the Chicago Cardinals, has long been the subject of controversy.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The controversy focuses on the suspension of the Pottsville Maroons by then NFL commissioner Joseph Carr, which prevented them for a chance at taking the title.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The Maroons were one of the dominant teams of the 1925 season, and after defeating the Chicago Cardinals 21–7 on December 6, they came away with the best record in the league.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] However, Carr suspended and removed the team from the NFL after they played an unauthorized exhibition game in Philadelphia, on the grounds that they had violated the territorial rights of that city's Frankford Yellow Jackets.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Chicago played and won two more games against weak NFL opponents, but were sanctioned because Cardinals player Art Folz hired four Chicago high school football players to play for the Milwaukee Badgers under assumed names to ensure a Cardinals victory.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Pottsville supporters argue that the suspension was illegitimate because the NFL did not grant exclusive territory rights at the time, and that in any event, they had oral league approval to play the game in Philadelphia.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Further, they argue that the Maroons, who were reinstated the next year, would have had the best record had they not been suspended.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Others claim that Chicago was the legitimate champion based on the rules of the time.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] In 1963, the NFL investigated and rejected Pottsville's case, refusing to reopen the case in 2003.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Both the NFL and the Pro Football Hall of Fame continue to list the Cardinals as the 1925 NFL champions.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Under the league rules during that time, the NFL title was automatically given to the team with the best record at the end of the season instead of having the winner be determined by a playoff tournament.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] There was an open-ended schedule during that season; although the final listed league games ended on December 6, teams could still schedule contests against each other through December 20 to make more money.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] On December 6, Pottsville defeated Chicago 21–7 to establish the best record in the league, and seemed to all but officially clinch the NFL championship.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The game against the Notre Dame All-Stars had been originally devised by Frankford.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] It was planned as non-league exhibition game between former Notre Dame stars and the top NFL team in the east; after defeating the Maroons 20–0, Frankford had believed they would indeed be the NFL's top eastern team.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] However, when they were later defeated by the Maroons in a second contest, they lost the right to play the game.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Instead, Pottsville would host the All-Stars at Minersville Park, while Frankford scheduled another league game against the Cleveland Bulldogs.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Pottsville was excited to host Notre Dame, hoping it would be a huge financial windfall for the team.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] However, they felt that Minersville Park, a high school field with a low capacity, was too small for such a big event.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Instead, they scheduled the game in Philadelphia, in the Yellow Jackets' territory.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Frankford protested to commissioner Carr, who warned the Maroons in writing that they faced suspension if they played in Philadelphia.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] However, the Maroons claimed that the league office orally approved the game during a telephone call.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] As a result of the suspension, Pottsville was prohibited from playing a scheduled game against the Providence Steam Roller or from completing its season.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Ironically, Frankford was hurriedly substituted for the game at Providence.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Meanwhile, Chicago scheduled and won two hastily arranged games against teams that had already disbanded for the season.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] This was within the NFL's rules at the time; teams were required to play eight league games, after which point they could either wrap up for the season, or schedule additional games to make more money.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Hoping for some more cash, the Cardinals arranged to play the Milwaukee Badgers and the Hammond Pros, both of whom had already dispersed.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Indeed, the Badgers were unable to bring back their full roster and resorted to substituting four high school players, which was in violation of NFL rules.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The NFL heavily sanctioned both Chicago and Milwaukee following their game, going so far as to force the Badgers owner to sell the team.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Carr said they would consider the game for removal from the standings; however, this never happened.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Cardinals owner Chris O'Brien was later offered but refused to accept the Championship title for his team.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] At the owners' meeting after the end of the season, he argued that his team did not deserve to take the title over a team that had beaten them fairly.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] It appears that his reasons for scheduling the Milwaukee and Hammond games had been not to take the title, but rather to convince the Chicago Bears to play his team again; the Bears, with Red Grange on their roster, were a very lucrative draw.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The NFL said it would revisit the issue later, but never did.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] It was only after the Bidwill family purchased the team in 1933 that the Cardinals began claiming the championship title.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] It is sometimes stated that Pottsville played a fairly easy schedule prior to their suspension, often facing teams that were less than full strength from playing the day before in Frankford, making Pottsville's case less sympathetic.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] However, the Maroons' final three games were against the Green Bay Packers, who finished the year at 8–5–1, the Yellow Jackets, who had beaten them earlier in the year and finished 13–7, and the Cardinals.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Pottsville won those games by scores of 31–0, 49-0 and 21–7, respectively, proving that they were a premier team.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] By 1963, the NFL appointed a special commission to examine the case, but voted 12–2 in favor of continuing to recognize the Cardinals as champions.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The lone dissenters were Art Rooney and George Halas, the then-owners of the Pittsburgh Steelers and the Chicago Bears, respectively.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] During this period, Charles "Stormy" Bidwill Jr., then head of the Chicago Cardinals, sent a letter to sports writer Red Smith opposing Pottsville’s attempt to be recognized as the 1925 NFL champions, describing the town as small and insignificant.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] In 2003, the issue was brought up again during the league's October owners meeting, where a suggestion to co-award the 1925 championship title received backing from Dan Rooney of the Pittsburgh Steelers, Jeffrey Lurie of the Philadelphia Eagles, Pottsville’s mayor John D.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] Reiley, and Pennsylvania’s governor Ed Rendell, but Bill Bidwill persuaded the owners to vote 30–2 against it.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] On December 10, 2007, the Pennsylvania House passed House Resolution 533 with full agreement, recognizing the achievements of the Pottsville Maroons and calling on the NFL to revisit the 1925 championship dispute, further amplifying advocacy efforts.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] One of the strongest opponents of a reversal has been the family of Charles Bidwill and his son Bill, who have controlled the Cardinals since 1933, and began to claim the 1925 title as their own.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The controversy involving territorial rights also led to the founding of the first American Football League after New York Giants owner Tim Mara objected to the leasing of Yankee Stadium and the application for an NFL franchise by C.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] When the NFL rejected Pyle's overture, he formed a competing league to showcase the talents of Red Grange and George "Wildcat" Wilson.
[src:american-football/1925-nfl-championship-controversy] The rival league folded after the 1926 season, and Mara relented, allowing Pyle to operate his team in the NFL and at Yankee Stadium.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] American football evolved in the United States, originating from the sports of soccer and rugby.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between two college teams, Rutgers and Princeton, using rules based on the rules of soccer at the time; by 1875, the sport had adopted rules similar to rugby union.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A set of rule changes drawn up from 1880 onward by Walter Camp, the "Father of American Football", established concepts that would define the sport, among them the snap, the line of scrimmage, eleven-player teams, and the concept of downs.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Later rule changes legalized the forward pass, created the neutral zone, and specified the size and shape of the football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The modern sport is closely related to Canadian football, which evolved in parallel with and at the same time as the American game; the two sports are considered the primary variants of gridiron football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] American football is the most popular sport in the United States; the most popular forms of the game are professional and college football, with the other major levels being high school and youth football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Over a million Americans played college or high school football in 2022, and the National Football League (NFL) has one of the highest average attendance of any professional sports league in the world.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Its championship game, the Super Bowl, ranks among the most-watched club sporting events globally.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Other professional and amateur leagues exist worldwide, but the sport does not have the international popularity of other American sports like baseball or basketball; the sport maintains a growing following in the rest of North America, Europe, Brazil, and Japan.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Flag football, a variant of the sport, will be played at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In the United States, American football is referred to as "football".
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The term "football" was officially established in the rulebook for the 1876 college football season, when the sport first shifted from soccer-style rules to rugby-style rules.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Although it could easily have been called "rugby" at this point, Harvard, one of the primary proponents of the rugby-style game, compromised and did not request the name of the sport be changed to "rugby".
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The terms "gridiron" or "American football" are favored in English-speaking countries where other types of football are popular, such as the United Kingdom, Ireland, New Zealand, and Australia.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] American football evolved from the sports of rugby and soccer.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Rugby, like American football, is a sport in which two competing teams vie for control of a ball, which can be kicked through a set of goalposts or run into the opponent's goal area to score points.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] What is considered to be the first American football game was played on November 6, 1869, between Rutgers and Princeton, two college teams.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] They consisted of 25 players per team and used a round ball that could not be picked up or carried.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] It could, however, be kicked or batted with the feet, hands, head, or sides, with the objective being to advance it into the opponent's goal.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Collegiate play continued for several years with games played using the rules of the host school.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Representatives of Yale, Columbia, Princeton and Rutgers met on October 19, 1873, to create a standard set of rules for use by all schools.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Teams were set at 20 players each, and fields of 400 by 250 feet (122 m × 76 m) were specified.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Harvard abstained from the conference, as they favored a rugby-style game that allowed running with the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] An 1875 Harvard–Yale game played under rugby-style rules was observed by two Princeton athletes who were impressed by it.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] They introduced the sport to Princeton, a feat the Professional Football Researchers Association compared to "selling refrigerators to Eskimos".
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Princeton, Harvard, Yale, and Columbia then agreed to intercollegiate play using a form of rugby union rules with a modified scoring system.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] These schools formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, although Yale did not join until 1879.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Yale player Walter Camp, now regarded as the "Father of American Football", secured rule changes in 1880 that reduced the size of each team from 15 to 11 players and instituted the snap to replace the chaotic and inconsistent scrum.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] While the game between Rutgers and Princeton is commonly considered the first American football game, several years prior in 1862, the Oneida Football Club formed as the oldest known football club in the United States.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The team consisted of graduates of Boston's elite preparatory schools and played from 1862 to 1865.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The introduction of the snap resulted in an unexpected consequence.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Before the snap, the strategy had been to punt if a scrum resulted in a bad field position.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] However, a group of Princeton players realized that, as the snap was uncontested, they could now hold the ball indefinitely to prevent their opponent from scoring.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 1881, in a game between Yale and Princeton, both teams used this strategy to maintain their undefeated records.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Each team held the ball, gaining no ground, for an entire half, resulting in a 0–0 tie.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] This "block game" proved extremely unpopular with both teams' spectators and fans.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A rule change was necessary to prevent this strategy from taking hold, and a reversion to the scrum was considered.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] However, Camp successfully proposed a rule in 1882 that limited each team to three downs, or tackles, to advance the ball 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Failure to advance the ball the required distance within those three downs would result in control of the ball being forfeited to the other team.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] This change effectively made American football a separate sport from rugby, and the resulting five-yard lines added to the field to measure distances made it resemble a gridiron in appearance.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Other major rule changes included a reduction of the field size to 110 by 53+1⁄3 yards (100.6 m × 48.8 m) and the adoption of a scoring system that awarded four points for a touchdown, two for a safety and a goal following a touchdown, and five for a goal from the field.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Additionally, tackling below the waist was legalized, and a static line of scrimmage was instituted.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Despite these new rules, football remained a violent sport.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Dangerous mass-formations like the flying wedge resulted in serious injuries and deaths.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A 1905 peak of 19 fatalities nationwide resulted in a threat by President Theodore Roosevelt to abolish the game unless major changes were made.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In response, 62 colleges and universities met in New York City to discuss rule changes on December 28, 1905.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] These proceedings resulted in the formation of the Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the United States, later renamed the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The legal forward pass was introduced in 1906, although its effect was initially minimal due to the restrictions placed on its use.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The idea of a 40-yard-wider field was opposed by Harvard due to the size of the new Harvard Stadium.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Other rule changes introduced that year included the reduction of playing time from 70 to 60 minutes and an increase of the distance required for a first down from 5 to 10 yards (4.6 to 9.1 m).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] To reduce infighting and dirty play between teams, the neutral zone was created along the width of the football before the snap.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Scoring was also adjusted: points awarded for field goals were reduced to three in 1909 and points for touchdowns were raised to six in 1912.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Also in 1912, the field was shortened to 100 yards (91 m) long, two 10-yard-long (9.1 m) end zones were created, and teams were given four downs instead of three to advance the ball 10 yards (9.1 m).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The roughing the passer penalty was implemented in 1914, and eligible players were first allowed to catch the ball anywhere on the field in 1918.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] On November 12, 1892, Pudge Heffelfinger was paid $500 (equivalent to $17,917 in 2025) to play a game for the Allegheny Athletic Association against the Pittsburgh Athletic Club.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Despite these extra benefits, the game had a strict sense of amateurism at the time, and direct payment to players was frowned upon, if not prohibited outright.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Over time, professional play became increasingly common, and with it came rising salaries and unpredictable player movement, as well as the illegal payment of college players who were still in school.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The National Football League (NFL), a group of professional teams that was originally established in 1920 as the American Professional Football Association, aimed to solve these problems.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] This new league's stated goals included an end to bidding wars over players, prevention of the use of college players, and abolition of the practice of paying players to leave another team.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] By 1922, the NFL had established itself as America's premier professional football league.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The dominant form of football at the time was played at the collegiate level.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The upstart NFL received a boost to its legitimacy in 1925, however, when an NFL team, the Pottsville Maroons, defeated a team of Notre Dame all-stars in an exhibition game.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A greater emphasis on the passing game helped professional football to distinguish itself further from the college game during the late 1930s.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Football, in general, became increasingly popular following the 1958 NFL Championship game between the Baltimore Colts and the New York Giants, still referred to as the "Greatest Game Ever Played".
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The game, a 23–17 overtime victory by the Colts, was seen by millions of television viewers and had a major influence on the popularity of the sport.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] By the mid-1960s, football was the most popular sport in the United States.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 1972, polling from Gallup, Inc. found that twice as many Americans identified football as their favorite sport (38%) as compared to baseball (19%); the sport has remained the most popular in the United States since.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 1960, the American Football League (AFL) was created to compete with the NFL.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The AFL began in relative obscurity but eventually thrived, with an initial television contract with the ABC television network.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The AFL's existence forced the conservative NFL to expand to Dallas and Minnesota in an attempt to destroy the new league.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Meanwhile, the AFL introduced many new features to professional football in the United States and actively recruited minority players.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The AFL also signed several star college players who had also been drafted by NFL teams.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Competition for players heated up in 1965, when the AFL New York Jets signed rookie Joe Namath to a then-record $437,000 contract (equivalent to $4.46 million in 2024).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A five-year, $40 million NBC television contract followed, which helped to sustain the young league.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The bidding war for players ended in 1966 when NFL owners approached the AFL regarding a merger, and the two leagues agreed on one that took full effect in 1970.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] This agreement provided for a common draft that would take place each year, and it instituted an annual World Championship game to be played between the champions of each league.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] This championship game, which would come to be known as the Super Bowl, began play at the end of the 1966 season.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Once the merger was completed, it was no longer a championship game between two leagues, instead being competed between the American Football Conference (AFC) and the National Football Conference (NFC).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Prior to the 1956 college football season, NCAA schools were organized into an upper University Division and lower College Division.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In the summer of 1973, the University Division became Division I, but by 1976, there was a desire to further separate the major football programs from those that were less financially successful, while still allowing their other sports to compete at the top level.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 1978, the NCAA divided Division I football into two subdivisions: NCAA Division I-A (known today as the Football Bowl Subdivision, or FBS) and Division I-AA (known today as the Football Championship Subdivision, or FCS).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The FCS adopted a single-elimination playoff structure to determine its champion, while the FBS retained its tradition of postseason bowl games.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Each bowl game was associated with a particular conference, and earning a spot in a major bowl game was the reward for winning a conference.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] This arrangement was beneficial to both conferences and bowl games, but it generally prevented the top-ranked teams from meeting in a true national championship game.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Because the NCAA itself does not officially sanction a Division I-FBS national champion, FBS national champions prior to 1992 were determined by polls, which frequently led to controversial or "split" national champions.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 1992, the Bowl Coalition was created to determine the national champion.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] It was replaced in 1995 by the Bowl Alliance, which itself gave way to the Bowl Championship Series (BCS) in 1997.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] All three of these systems consisted of a single national championship game, as well as a set of other major bowl games.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 2014, the BCS was replaced by the College Football Playoff (CFP), a single-elimination tournament.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In another major change, in 2021, following legal pressure and antitrust lawsuits, the NCAA and its conferences began allowing schools to offer compensation to student athletes for the use of their names, images, and likenesses (NIL).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] NCAA* allowed schools to directly pay players, ending the traditionally amateur nature of college athletics in the United States.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A football game is played between two teams of 11 players each.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Playing with more on the field is punishable by a penalty.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Teams may substitute any number of their players between downs; this "platoon" system has resulted in teams utilizing specialized offensive, defensive and special teams units.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The number of players allowed on an active roster varies by league; the NFL has a 53-man roster, while NCAA Division I allows teams to have up to 105 players on their roster.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Individual players in a football game must be designated with a uniform number between 0 and 99.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] NFL teams are required to number their players by a league-approved numbering system, and any exceptions must be approved by the commissioner.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] NCAA and NFHS teams are "strongly advised" to number their offensive players according to a league-suggested numbering scheme.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Women are eligible to play in high school, college, and professional football, but most football players are men.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] No woman has ever played in the NFL, but women have played in high school and college football games.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In 2018, women and girls comprised 0.5% of players in Pop Warner Little Scholars youth football, 0.2% of players in high school football, and 10.9% of Americans who report playing tackle football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The role of the offensive unit is to advance the football down the field with the ultimate goal of scoring a touchdown.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The offensive team must line up in a legal formation before they can snap the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] An offensive formation is considered illegal if there are more than four players in the backfield or fewer than five players numbered 50–79 on the offensive line.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Players can line up temporarily in a position whose eligibility is different from what their number permits as long as they report the change immediately to the referee, who then informs the defensive team of the change.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Neither team's players, except the center (C), are allowed to line up in or cross the neutral zone until the ball is snapped.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Interior offensive linemen are not allowed to move until the snap of the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The main backfield positions are the quarterback (QB), running back (RB), and fullback (FB).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The quarterback is the leader of the offense.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Either the quarterback or a coach calls the plays.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Quarterbacks typically inform the rest of the offense of the play in the huddle before the team lines up.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The quarterback lines up behind the center to take the snap and then hands the ball off, throws it, or runs with it.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The primary role of the running back is to carry the ball on running plays.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Fullbacks tend to be larger than halfbacks and function primarily as blockers, but they are sometimes used as runners in short-yardage or goal-line situations.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The offensive line (OL) consists of several players whose primary function is to block members of the defensive line from tackling the ball carrier on running plays or sacking the quarterback on passing plays.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The most important role on the offensive line is the center, who is not just responsible for blocking and snapping the ball, but also for handling line adjustments and pre-snap strategy.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] On either side of the center are the guards (G), while tackles (T) line up outside the guards.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The principal receivers are the wide receivers (WR) and the tight ends (TE).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Wide receivers line up on or near the line of scrimmage, split outside the line.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The main goal of the wide receiver is to catch passes thrown by the quarterback, but they may also function as decoys or as blockers during running plays.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Tight ends line up next to the offensive line and function both as receivers and as blockers.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The role of the defense is to prevent the offense from scoring by tackling the ball carrier or by forcing turnovers.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Turnovers include interceptions (a defender catching a forward pass intended for the offense) and forced fumbles (taking possession of the ball from the ball-carrier).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The defensive line (DL) consists of defensive ends (DE) and defensive tackles (DT).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Defensive ends line up on the ends of the defensive line, while defensive tackles line up on the inside, between the defensive ends.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The primary responsibilities of defensive ends and defensive tackles are to stop running plays on the outside and inside, respectively, to pressure the quarterback on passing plays, and to occupy the line so that the linebackers can break through.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Linebackers line up behind the defensive line but in front of the defensive backfield.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] They are divided into two types: middle linebackers (MLB) and outside linebackers (OLB).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Linebackers tend to serve as the defensive leaders and call the defensive plays, given their vantage point of the offensive backfield.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Their roles include defending the run, pressuring the quarterback, and tackling backs, wide receivers, and tight ends.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The defensive backfield, often called the secondary, consists of cornerbacks (CB) and safeties (S).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Safeties are themselves divided into free safeties (FS) and strong safeties (SS).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Cornerbacks line up outside the defensive formation, typically opposite a receiver to be able to cover them.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Safeties line up between the cornerbacks but farther back in the secondary.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Safeties tend to be viewed as "the last line of defense" and are responsible for stopping deep passing plays as well as breakout running plays.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The special teams unit is responsible for all kicking plays.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The special teams unit of the team in control of the ball tries to execute field goal (FG) attempts, punts, and kickoffs, while the opposing team's unit will aim to block or return them.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Three positions are specific to the field goal and PAT (point after touchdown) unit: the placekicker (K or PK), holder (H), and long snapper (LS).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The long snapper's job is to snap the football to the holder, who will catch and place it on the ground for the kicker.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] There is usually never a holder on kickoffs, because the ball is kicked off a tee; however, a holder may be used in certain situations, such as if wind is preventing the ball from remaining upright on the tee.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The player on the receiving team who catches the ball is known as the kick returner (KR).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The positions specific to punt plays are the punter (P), long snapper, upback, and gunner.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The long snapper snaps the football directly to the punter, who then drops and kicks it before it hits the ground.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Gunners line up split outside the line and race down the field, aiming to tackle the punt returner (PR)—the player who catches the punt.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Upbacks line up a short distance, typically 1-7 yards, behind the line of scrimmage, providing additional protection to the punter.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In football, the winner is the team that has scored more points at the end of the game.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] There are multiple ways to score in a football game.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The touchdown (TD), worth six points, is the most valuable scoring play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A touchdown is scored when a live ball is advanced into, caught, or recovered in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The scoring team then attempts a try, more commonly known as the point(s)-after-touchdown (PAT) or conversion, which is a single scoring opportunity.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by a place kick or drop kick through the goal posts, it is worth one point, typically called the extra point.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If the PAT is scored by what would normally be a touchdown, it is worth two points; this is known as a two-point conversion.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In general, the extra point is almost always successful, while the two-point conversion is a much riskier play with a higher probability of failure; accordingly, extra point attempts are far more common than two-point conversion attempts.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A field goal (FG), worth three points, is scored when the ball is place kicked or drop kicked through the uprights and over the crossbars of the defense's goalposts.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Almost all field goal attempts are done via place kick.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] While drop kicks were common in the early days of the sport, the shape of modern footballs makes it difficult to reliably drop kick the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The last successful scoring play by drop kick in the NFL was accomplished in 2006; prior to that, the last successful drop kick had been made in 1941.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] After a PAT attempt or successful field goal, the scoring team must kick the ball off to the other team.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A safety is scored when the ball carrier is tackled in the carrier's own end zone.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Safeties are worth two points, which are awarded to the defense.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In addition, the team that conceded the safety must kick the ball to the scoring team via a free kick.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Safeties are the least common method of scoring in football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Football games are played on a rectangular field that measures 120 yards (110 m) long and 53+1⁄3 yards (48.8 m) wide.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Lines marked along the ends and sides of the field are known as the end lines and sidelines.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Goal lines are marked 10 yards (9.1 m) inward from each end line.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Weighted pylons are placed along each sideline, on the inside corner of the intersections with the goal lines and end lines.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] White markings on the field identify the distance from the end zone.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Inbound lines, or hash marks, are short parallel lines that mark off 1-yard (0.91 m) increments.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Yard lines, which can run the width of the field, are marked every 5 yards (4.6 m).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A one-yard-wide line is placed at each end of the field; this line is marked at the center of the two-yard line in professional play and at the three-yard line in college play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Numerals that display the distance from the closest goal line in yards are placed on both sides of the field every ten yards.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Goalposts are located at the center of the plane of the two end lines.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The crossbar of these posts is 10 feet (3.0 m) above the ground, with vertical uprights at the end of the crossbar 18 feet 6 inches (5.64 m) apart for professional and collegiate play, and 23 feet 4 inches (7.11 m) apart for high school play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The uprights extend vertically 35 feet (11 m) on professional fields, a minimum of 10 yards (9.1 m) on college fields, and a minimum of 10 feet (3.0 m) on high school fields.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Goal posts are padded at the base, and orange ribbons are normally placed at the tip of each upright as indicators of wind strength and direction.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The football itself is a prolate spheroid leather ball, similar to the balls used in rugby or Australian rules football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] At all levels of play, the football is inflated to 12+1⁄2 to 13+1⁄2 psi (86 to 93 kPa), or just under one atmosphere, and weighs 14 to 15 ounces (400 to 430 g); beyond that, the exact dimensions vary slightly.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In professional play the ball has a long axis of 11 to 11+1⁄4 inches (28 to 29 cm), a long circumference of 28 to 28+1⁄2 inches (71 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 21 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In college and high school play the ball has a long axis of 10+7⁄8 to 11+7⁄16 inches (27.6 to 29.1 cm), a long circumference of 27+3⁄4 to 28+1⁄2 inches (70 to 72 cm), and a short circumference of 20+3⁄4 to 21+1⁄4 inches (53 to 54 cm).
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Football games last for a total of 60 minutes in professional and college play and are divided into two halves of 30 minutes and four quarters of 15 minutes.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] High school football games are 48 minutes in length with two halves of 24 minutes and four quarters of 12 minutes.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The two halves are separated by a halftime period, and the first and third quarters are followed by a short break.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Before the game starts, the referee and each team's captain meet at midfield for a coin toss.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The visiting team can call either "heads" or "tails"; the winner of the toss chooses whether to receive or kick off the ball or which goal they wish to defend.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] They can defer their choice until the second half.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Unless the winning team decides to defer, the losing team chooses the option the winning team did not select—to receive, kick, or select a goal to defend to begin the second half.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Most teams choose to receive or defer, because choosing to kick the ball to start the game allows the other team to choose which goal to defend.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Teams switch goals following the first and third quarters.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If a down is in progress when a quarter ends, play continues until the down is completed.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If certain fouls are committed during play while time has expired, the quarter may be extended through an untimed down.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Games last longer than their defined length due to play stoppages—the average NFL game lasts slightly over three hours.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Time in a football game is measured by the game clock.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] An operator is responsible for starting, stopping and operating the game clock based on the direction of the appropriate official.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A separate play clock is used to show the amount of time within which the offense must initiate a play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The play clock is set to 25 seconds after certain administrative stoppages in play and to 40 seconds when play is proceeding without such stoppages.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If the offense fails to start a play before the play clock reads "00", a delay of game foul is called on the offense.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] There are two main ways the offense can advance the ball: running and passing.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In a typical play, the center passes the ball backwards and between their legs to the quarterback in a process known as the snap.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The quarterback then either hands the ball off to a running back, throws the ball, or runs with it.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The play ends when the player with the ball is tackled or goes out-of-bounds or a pass hits the ground without a player having caught it.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A forward pass can be legally attempted only if the passer is behind the line of scrimmage; only one forward pass can be attempted per down.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] As in rugby, players can also pass the ball backwards at any point during a play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In the NFL, a down also ends immediately if the runner's helmet comes off.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The offense is given a series of four plays, known as downs.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If the offense advances ten or more yards in the four downs, they are awarded a new set of four downs.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If they fail to advance ten yards, possession of the football is turned over to the defense.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] In most situations, if the offense reaches their fourth down they will punt the ball to the other team, which forces them to begin their drive from farther down the field; if they are in field goal range, they might attempt to score a field goal instead.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A group of officials, the chain crew, keeps track of both the downs and the distance measurements.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The spot needed to secure a first down is known as the line to gain.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] On television, a yellow line is electronically superimposed on the field to show the line to gain to the viewing audience.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] There are two categories of kicks in football: scrimmage kicks, which can be executed by the offensive team on any down from behind or on the line of scrimmage, and free kicks.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The free kicks are the kickoff, which starts the first and third quarters and overtime and follows a try attempt or a successful field goal, and the safety kick, which follows a safety.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] On a kickoff, the ball is placed at the 35-yard line of the kicking team in professional and college play and at the 40-yard line in high school play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The ball may be drop kicked or place kicked.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If a place kick is chosen, the ball can be placed on the ground or a tee; a holder may be used in either case.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] On a safety kick, the kicking team kicks the ball from their own 20-yard line.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] They can punt, drop kick or place kick the ball, but a tee may not be used in professional play.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Any member of the receiving team may catch or advance the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The ball may be recovered by the kicking team once it has gone at least ten yards and has touched the ground or has been touched by any member of the receiving team.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The three types of scrimmage kicks are place kicks, drop kicks, and punts.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Only place kicks and drop kicks can score points.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The place kick is the standard method used to score points, because the pointy shape of the football makes it difficult to reliably drop kick.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Once the ball has been kicked from a scrimmage kick, it can be advanced by the kicking team only if it is caught or recovered behind the line of scrimmage.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] If it is touched or recovered by the kicking team beyond this line, it becomes dead at the spot where it was touched.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The kicking team is prohibited from interfering with the receiver's opportunity to catch the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The receiving team has the option of signaling for a fair catch, which prohibits the defense from blocking into or tackling the receiver.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The play ends as soon as the ball is caught, and the ball may not be advanced.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Officials are responsible for enforcing game rules and monitoring the clock.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] All officials carry a whistle and wear black-and-white striped shirts and black hats, except for the referee, whose hat is white.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Each carries a weighted yellow flag that is thrown to the ground to signal that a foul has been called.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] An official who spots multiple fouls will throw their hat as a secondary signal.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Women can serve as officials; Sarah Thomas became the NFL's first female official in 2015.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Another set of officials, the chain crew, are responsible for moving the chains.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The chains, consisting of two large sticks with a 10-yard-long chain between them, are used to measure for a first down.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The chain crew stays on the sidelines during the game, but if requested by the officials, they will briefly bring the chains onto the field to measure.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A typical chain crew will have at least three people—two members of the chain crew will hold either of the two sticks, while a third will hold the down marker.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The down marker, a large stick with a dial on it, is flipped after each play to indicate the current down and is typically moved to the approximate spot of the ball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The chain crew system has been used for over 100 years and is considered an accurate measure of distance, rarely subject to criticism from either side.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Football is a full-contact sport, and injuries are relatively common.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur during training sessions, particularly ones that involve contact between players.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] To try to prevent injuries, players are required to wear a set of equipment.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] At a minimum players must wear a football helmet and a set of shoulder pads, but individual leagues may require additional padding such as thigh pads and guards, knee pads, chest protectors, and mouthguards.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Most injuries occur in the lower extremities, particularly in the knee, but a significant number also affect the upper extremities.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] The most common types of injuries are strains, sprains, bruises, fractures, dislocations, and concussions.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Repeated concussions (and possibly sub-concussive head impacts) can increase a person's risk in later life for CTE (chronic traumatic encephalopathy) and health issues such as dementia, Parkinson's disease, and depression.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Concussions are often caused by helmet-to-helmet or upper-body contact between opposing players, although helmets have prevented more serious injuries such as skull fractures.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] However, a study in the *Orthopaedic Journal of Sports Medicine* found that Heads Up Football was ineffective; the same study noted that more extensive reforms implemented by Pop Warner Little Scholars and its member teams were effective in significantly reducing concussion rates.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] A 2018 study performed by the VA Boston Healthcare System and the Boston University School of Medicine found that tackle football before age 12 was correlated with earlier onset of symptoms of CTE, but not with increased symptom severity.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] More specifically, each year a player played tackle football under age 12 predicted earlier onset of cognitive, behavioral, and mood problems by an average of two and a half years.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] To help mitigate injuries, the NCAA recommends limiting full contact (tackling to the ground) practices, avoiding full contact on consecutive days, and no more than 20 hours of practice per week.
[src:american-football/american-football-p01] Players must receive one day off per week.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The National Football League (NFL) and the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) are the most popular football leagues in the United States.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The National Football League was founded in 1920 and has since become the largest and most popular sport in the United States.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NFL has the highest average attendance of any sporting league in the world, with an average attendance of 66,960 during the 2011 NFL season.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NFL championship game is called the Super Bowl, and is among the biggest events in club sports worldwide.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] It is played between the champions of the National Football Conference (NFC) and the American Football Conference (AFC), and its winner is awarded the Vince Lombardi Trophy.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] College football is the third-most popular sport in the United States, behind professional football and professional baseball, respectively.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NCAA, the largest collegiate organization, is divided into three Divisions: Division I, Division II and Division III.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Division I is the highest level of play, while Division III is the lowest; Division I and II programs can offer athletic scholarships to student-athletes, while Division III programs cannot.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Division I football is further divided into two subdivisions: the Football Bowl Subdivision (FBS) and the Football Championship Subdivision (FCS).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The champions of each level of play are determined through playoff systems.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Other national college football organizations include the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), which comprises around 90 smaller colleges, and the National Junior College Athletic Association (NJCAA), whose membership consists of two-year colleges.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] High school football is the most popular sport in the United States played by boys.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NFHS is the largest organization for high school football, with member associations in all 50 states as well as the District of Columbia.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] USA Football is the governing body for youth and amateur football, and Pop Warner Little Scholars is the largest organization for youth football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The most successful league to directly compete with the NFL was the American Football League (AFL), which existed from 1960 to 1969.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The AFL became a significant rival in 1964 before signing a five-year, US$36 million television deal with NBC.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] AFL teams began signing NFL players to contracts, and the league's popularity grew to challenge that of the NFL.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged in the 1970 season, and all the AFL teams joined the NFL.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] An earlier league, the All-America Football Conference (AAFC), was in play from 1946 to 1949.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] After it had dissolved, two AAFC teams, the Cleveland Browns and the San Francisco 49ers, became members of the NFL; another member, the Baltimore Colts joined the league, but folded after just a year in the NFL.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Other attempts to start rival leagues since the AFL merged with the NFL in 1970 have been far less successful, as professional football salaries and the NFL's television contracts began to escalate out of the reach of competitors and the NFL covered more of the larger cities.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The World Football League (WFL) played for two seasons, in 1974 and 1975, but faced such severe monetary issues it could not pay its players.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In its second and final season the WFL attempted to establish a stable credit rating, but the league disbanded before the season could be completed.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The United States Football League (USFL) operated for three seasons from 1983 to 1985.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Originally not intended as a rival league, the entry of owners who sought marquee talent and to challenge the NFL led to an escalation in salaries and ensuing financial losses.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] A subsequent US$1.5 billion antitrust lawsuit against the NFL was successful in court, but the league was awarded only $1 in damages, which was automatically tripled to $3 under antitrust law.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The original XFL, created in 2001 by WWE co-founder Vince McMahon, lasted for only one season.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Despite television contracts with NBC and UPN, and high expectations, the XFL suffered from low quality of play and poor reception for its use of tawdry professional wrestling gimmicks, which caused initially high ratings and attendance to collapse.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The United Football League (UFL) began in 2009 but folded after suspending its 2012 season after having lost $120 million over just three seasons.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Another spring league, the Alliance of American Football lasted less than one season, unable to keep investors.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] A revived United States Football League began play in 2022 and quickly faced immediate competition from the XFL, which resumed play in 2023.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The two leagues merged following the 2023 season, forming a new United Football League (UFL).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] American football leagues exist throughout the world, but the game has yet to achieve the international success and popularity of baseball and basketball.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] At the international level, Canada, Mexico, and Japan are considered to be second-tier, while Austria, Germany, and France would rank among a third tier.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] These countries rank far below the United States, which is dominant at the international level.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] NFL Europa, the developmental league of the NFL, operated from 1991 to 1992 and then from 1995 to 2007.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] At the time of its closure, NFL Europa had five teams based in Germany and one in the Netherlands.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In Germany, the German Football League (GFL) has 16 teams and has operated for over 40 seasons, with the league's championship game, the German Bowl, closing out each season.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The league operates in a promotion and relegation structure with German Football League 2 (GFL2), which also has 16 teams.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The United Kingdom also operated several teams within NFL Europe during the League's tenure.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The resulting rise in popularity of the sport brought the NFL back to the country in 2007 where they now hold the NFL International Series in London, currently consisting of four regular season games.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The continuing interest and growth in both the sport and the series has led to the possible formation of a potential NFL franchise in London.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] NFL commissioner Roger Goodell aims to host 16 international games each year, enough for each NFL team to play one international game each year.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom, the British American Football Association National Leagues (BAFANL), an amateur competition, is the top level of American football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Teams compete across multiple levels in a promotion and relegation structure; the league's championship is the Britbowl.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] University competition is held through the British Universities American Football League (BUAFL), which was formed in 2007.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In 2008, the league launched a partnership with the NFL, through its partner organization NFL UK.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] From 2007 to 2014, the BUAFL grew from 42 teams and 2,460 participants to 75 teams and over 4,100 people involved.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The standard form of American football is not an Olympic sport, but it was a demonstration sport at the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The International Federation of American Football (IFAF), an international governing body composed of continental federations, received provisional recognition from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) in 2014 and was fully recognized by the IOC in 2015.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] American football federations are present in Africa, the Americas, Asia, Europe, and Oceania; a total of 75 national football federations exist as of 2023.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The IFAF runs tournaments such as the IFAF World Championship, the IFAF Women's World Championship, the IFAF Junior World Championship, and the Flag Football World Championship.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Obstacles towards the goal of becoming an Olympic sport included the predominant participation of men in international play and the short three-week Olympic schedule.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Large team sizes were an additional difficulty, due to the Olympics' set limit of 10,500 athletes and coaches.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] American football also faced an issue with a lack of global visibility.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Nigel Melville, the CEO of USA Rugby, noted that "American football is recognized globally as a sport, but it's not played globally." To solve these concerns, major effort was put into promoting flag football, a modified version of American football, at the international level.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Flag football for men and women will debut as an Olympic sport at the 2028 Summer Olympics.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] "Baseball is still called the national pastime, but football is by far the more popular sport in American society", according to ESPN.com's Sean McAdam.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In a 2014 poll conducted by Harris Interactive, professional football ranked as the most popular sport, and college football ranked third behind only professional football and baseball; 46% of participants ranked some form of the game as their favorite sport.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Professional football has ranked as the most popular sport in the poll since 1985, when it surpassed baseball for the first time.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Professional football is most popular among those who live in the eastern United States and rural areas, while college football is most popular in the southern United States and among people with graduate and post-graduate degrees.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Football is also the most-played sport by high school and college athletes in the United States.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] A 2022 survey from National Football Foundation found that one million high-school athletes played the sport, with another 81,000 college athletes across both the NCAA and the NAIA.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The Super Bowl is the most popular single-day sporting event in the United States, and is among the biggest club sporting events in the world in terms of TV viewership.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NFL made approximately $12 billion in revenue in 2022.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Super Bowl games account for eight of the top ten most-watched broadcasts in American history; Super Bowl LVII, played on February 12, 2023, was watched by a record 115.1 million Americans, and is second only to the Apollo 11 moon landing (125 million viewers).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NFL is the most valuable sports league in the world, with the average team valued at over $8 billion.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] American football also plays a significant role in American culture.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The day on which the Super Bowl is held is considered a *de facto* national holiday, and in parts of the country like Texas, the sport has been compared to a religion.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Football is also linked to other holidays; New Year's Day is traditionally the date for several college football bowl games, including the Rose Bowl.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] However, if New Year's Day is on a Sunday, the bowl games are moved to another date so as not to conflict with the typical NFL Sunday schedule.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Thanksgiving football is another American tradition, hosting many high school, college, and professional games.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Implicit rules such as playing through pain and sacrificing for the better of the team are promoted in football culture.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In Canada, the game has a significant following.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] According to a 2013 poll, 21% of respondents said they followed the NFL "very closely" or "fairly closely", making it the third-most followed league behind the National Hockey League (NHL) and Canadian Football League (CFL).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] American football also has a long history in Mexico, which was introduced to the sport in 1896.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] It was the second-most popular sport in Mexico in the 1950s, with the game being particularly popular in colleges.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The *Los Angeles Times* notes the NFL claims over 16 million fans in Mexico, which places the country third behind the U.S. and Canada.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] American football is played in Mexico both professionally and as part of the college sports system.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] A professional league, the Liga de Fútbol Americano Profesional (LFA), was founded in 2016.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Japan was introduced to the sport in 1934 by Paul Rusch, a teacher and Christian missionary who helped to establish football teams at three universities in Tokyo.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Play was halted during World War II by order of Emperor Hirohito, but the sport began growing in popularity again after the war.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] As of 2010, there are more than 400 high school football teams in Japan, with over 15,000 participants, and over 100 teams play in the Kantoh Collegiate Football Association (KCFA).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The X-League is the largest American football league in Japan, and the largest American football league in the world to use a promotion-relegation system.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Some teams in the X-League, like the Panasonic Impulse, are sponsored by corporations, and all Japanese players on these teams are employed by the corporation.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The league operates in separate spring and fall seasons, with each team playing five games.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The top eight teams make the playoffs, which are played in Tokyo Dome; the champion is determined by the Rice Bowl.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Europe is a major target for the expansion of the game by football organizers.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In the United Kingdom in the 1980s, the sport was popular, with the 1986 Super Bowl being watched by over four million people (about 1 out of every 14 Britons).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Its popularity faded during the 1990s, coinciding with the establishment of the Premier League—the top level of the English association football (soccer) league system.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] According to BBC America, there is a "social stigma" surrounding American football in the UK, with many Brits feeling the sport has no right to call itself "football" due to the lack of emphasis on kicking.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Nonetheless, the sport has retained a following in the United Kingdom; the NFL operates a media network in the country, and since 2007 has hosted the NFL International Series in London.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Super Bowl viewership has also rebounded, with over 4.4 million Britons watching Super Bowl XLVI.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The sport is played in European countries like Switzerland, which has American football clubs in every major city, and Germany, where the sport has around 45,000 registered amateur players.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] It was generally unknown there until the 1980s when a small group of players began playing on Copacabana Beach in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The sport grew gradually with 700 amateur players registering within 20 years.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Games were played on the beach with modified rules and without the traditional football equipment due to its lack of availability in Brazil.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Eventually, a tournament, the Carioca championship, was founded, with the championship Carioca Bowl played to determine a league champion.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The country saw its first full-pad game of football in October 2008.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] According to *The Rio Times*, the sport is one of the fastest-growing sports in Brazil and is almost as commonly played as soccer on the beaches of Copacabana and Botafogo.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Football in Brazil is governed by the Confederação Brasileira de Futebol Americano (CBFA), which had over 5,000 registered players as of November 2013.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The sport's increase in popularity has been attributed to games aired on ESPN, which began airing in Brazil in 1992 with Portuguese commentary.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The popularity and "easy accessibility" of non-contact versions of the sport in Brazil has led to a rise in participation by female players.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] According to ESPN, the American football audience in Brazil increased 800% between 2013 and 2016.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The network, along with Esporte Interativo, airs games there on cable television.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] NFL had expressed interest in having games in the country, eventually resulting in São Paulo's Arena Corinthians hosting Brazil's first NFL game in 2024, and the Super Bowl has become a widely watched event in Brazil at bars and movie theaters.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Further countries have also expressed interest in football to a lesser degree.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The Arab world has expressed growing interest in American football, with many countries in the region being members of IFAF Asia.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Jordan and the United Arab Emirates, which are not members of IFAF, have established their own domestic leagues.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Egypt established two leagues for the sport, namely the Egyptian League of American Football and the Egyptian Federation of American Football, and Saudi Arabia hosts two teams based out of Jeddah and Yanbu respectively.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] China has additionally been a target for the expansion of the sport, with the Mainland being the home of the Chinese National Football League as well as a growing audience of Super Bowl watchers.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Three franchises are also based out of Hong Kong, which prior to the COVID-19 pandemic regularly played mainland teams.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] NFL games average 900,000 viewers in China, though the league has cited logistical challenges which would prevent teams from playing games akin to abroad games in European countries.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Canadian football, the predominant form of football in Canada, is closely related to American football—both sports developed from rugby and are considered to be the chief variants of gridiron football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The Canadian Football League (CFL) is the major Canadian league and is the second-most popular sporting league in Canada, behind the National Hockey League.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Football Canada is the governing body for amateur Canadian football, and is also member of the International Federation of American Football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] NFL players have played in the CFL and vice versa; quarterback Warren Moon is the only player in both Canadian Football Hall of Fame and the Pro Football Hall of Fame.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The NFL and CFL had a formal working relationship from 1997 to 2006.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The CFL has a strategic partnership with two American football leagues, the German Football League (GFL) and the Liga de Futbol Americano Profesional (LFA).
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Rule changes announced in 2025 by the CFL will bring some elements of the sport closer to those of American football, while retaining the larger number of players, wider field, and three-down limit.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The Indoor Football League is an example of a prominent indoor league.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] The Arena Football League, which was founded in 1987 and ceased operations in 2019, was one of the longest-lived indoor football leagues.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In 2004, the league was called "America's fifth major sport" by *ESPN The Magazine*.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Some schools that lack the enrollment numbers to run a competitive 11-man team choose to play nine-man, eight-man, or six-man football, which utilize modified rules to account for smaller team sizes.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] There are several non-contact variants of football, such as flag football.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] In flag football the ball-carrier is not tackled; instead, defenders aim to pull a flag tied around the ball-carrier's waist.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Flag football has become increasingly popular due to its lower likelihood of head injuries and its openness to female athletes; according to the NFL, which promotes flag football through NFL Flag, roughly 25% of flag football players are women and girls.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Another variant, touch football, simply requires the ball-carrier to be touched to be considered downed.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Depending on the rules used, a game of touch football may require the ball-carrier be touched with either one or two hands to be considered downed.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Wheelchair football is a parasport adapting the rules of football for people with physical disabilities.
[src:american-football/american-football-p02] Although it uses touch rules instead of tackling, wheelchair football isn't a non-contact sport; participants engage in both "big hits" and "physical blocks".
